WEBVTT

00:14.220 --> 00:17.260
XXIX. Huck Saves the Widow.

00:18.320 --> 00:24.170
The first thing Tom heard on Friday morning was a glad piece of news. Judge Thatcher's

00:24.170 --> 00:29.910
family had come back to town the night before. Both Inge and Joe and the treasurer sank

00:29.910 --> 00:34.770
into secondary importance for a moment, and Becky took the chief place in the boy's interest.

00:35.130 --> 00:41.370
He saw her, and they had an exhausting good time playing High Spy and Gully Keeper with

00:41.370 --> 00:46.830
a crowd of their schoolmates. The day was completed and crowned in a peculiarly satisfactory

00:46.830 --> 00:52.210
way. Becky teased her mother to appoint the next day for the long-promised and long-delayed

00:52.210 --> 00:58.830
picnic, and she consented. The child's delight was boundless, and Tom's not more moderate.

00:59.390 --> 01:04.190
The invitations were sent out before sunset, and straightway the young folks of the village

01:04.190 --> 01:10.090
were thrown into a fever of preparation and pleasurable anticipation. Tom's excitement

01:10.090 --> 01:15.650
enabled him to keep awake until a pretty late hour, and he had good hopes of hearing Huck's

01:15.650 --> 01:22.710
and of having his treasure to astonish Becky and the picnickers with next day. But he was

01:22.710 --> 01:29.470
disappointed. No signal came that night. Morning came, eventually, and by ten or eleven o'clock

01:29.470 --> 01:34.450
a giddy and rollicking company were gathered at Judge Thatcher's, and everything was ready

01:34.450 --> 01:39.770
for a start. It was not the custom for elderly people to mar picnics with their presence.

01:40.090 --> 01:44.530
The children were considered safe enough under the wings of a few young ladies of eighteen,

01:44.530 --> 01:49.990
and a few young gentlemen of twenty-three or thereabouts. The old steam ferry-boat

01:49.990 --> 01:55.250
was chartered for the occasion. Presently the gay throng filed up the main street laden

01:55.250 --> 02:01.010
with provision baskets. Sid was sick, and had to miss the fun. Mary remained at home

02:01.010 --> 02:04.750
to entertain him. The last thing Mrs. Thatcher said to Becky was,

02:05.170 --> 02:09.730
"'You'll not get back till late. Perhaps you'd better stay all night with some of the girls

02:09.730 --> 02:12.290
that live near the ferry landing, child.'

02:12.290 --> 02:14.830
"'Then I'll stay with Susy Harper, Mama.'

02:14.830 --> 02:18.990
"'Very well. And mind and behave yourself, and don't be any trouble.'

02:19.850 --> 02:22.610
Presently, as they tripped along, Tom said to Becky,

02:23.570 --> 02:28.410
"'Say, I'll tell you what we'll do. Instead of going to Joe Harper's, we'll climb right

02:28.410 --> 02:33.990
up the hill and stop at the Widow Douglas's. She'll have ice cream—she has it most every

02:34.530 --> 02:38.310
day—dead loads of it—and she'll be awful glad to have us.'

02:38.310 --> 02:40.610
"'Oh, that will be fun!'

02:40.610 --> 02:42.370
Then Becky reflected a moment and said,

02:42.610 --> 02:44.310
"'But what will Mama say?'

02:44.310 --> 02:45.850
"'All she'll ever know.'

02:45.850 --> 02:49.470
The girl turned the idea over in her mind, and said reluctantly,

02:50.030 --> 02:52.310
"'I reckon it's wrong, but—'

02:52.390 --> 02:57.130
"'But, shucks, your mother won't know, and so what's the harm? All she wants is that

02:57.130 --> 03:02.270
you'll be safe. And I bet you she'd have said, Go there, if she'd a thought about it. I know

03:02.270 --> 03:03.330
she would.'

03:03.330 --> 03:08.830
The Widow Douglas's splendid hospitality was a tempting bait. It and Tom's persuasions

03:08.830 --> 03:13.270
presently carried the day, so it was decided to say nothing to anybody about the night's

03:13.270 --> 03:17.950
program. Presently it occurred to Tom that maybe Huck might come in this very night and

03:17.950 --> 03:22.850
give the signal. The thought took a deal of the spirit out of his anticipation. Still,

03:22.850 --> 03:27.550
he could not bear to give up the fun at Widow Douglas's. And why should he give it up, he

03:27.550 --> 03:31.970
reasoned? The signal did not come the night before, so why should it be any more likely

03:31.970 --> 03:38.090
to come to-night? The sure fun of the evening outweighed the uncertain treasure, and, boylike,

03:38.210 --> 03:42.810
he determined to yield to the stronger inclination and not allow himself to think of the box

03:42.810 --> 03:44.390
of money another time that day.

03:45.270 --> 03:49.610
Three miles below town the ferry-boat stopped at the mouth of the woody hollow and tied

03:49.610 --> 03:55.250
up. The crowd swarmed ashore, and soon the forest distances and craggy heights echoed

03:55.250 --> 04:00.210
far and near with shoutings and laughter. All the different ways of getting hot and tired

04:00.210 --> 04:06.210
with, and by and by the rovers straggled back to camp, fortified with responsible appetites,

04:06.490 --> 04:11.510
and then the destruction of the good things began. After the feast there was a refreshing

04:11.510 --> 04:16.350
season of rest and chat in the shade of spreading oaks. By and by somebody shouted,

04:16.790 --> 04:18.430
"'Who's ready for the cave?'

04:19.310 --> 04:24.350
"'Everybody was.' Bundles of candles were procured, and straight away there was a general

04:24.350 --> 04:29.330
scamper up the hill. The mouth of the cave was up the hillside, an opening shaped like

04:29.330 --> 04:35.470
the letter A. Its massive oaken door stood unbarred. Within was a small chamber, chilly

04:35.470 --> 04:40.730
as an ice-house, and walled by nature with solid limestone that was dewy with a cold

04:40.730 --> 04:46.670
sweat. It was romantic and mysterious to stand here in the deep gloom and look out upon the

04:46.670 --> 04:52.330
green valley shining in the sun. But the impressiveness of the situation quickly wore off, and the

04:52.330 --> 04:57.270
romping began again. The moment a candle was lighted there was a general rush upon the

04:57.270 --> 05:01.950
owner of it. A struggle and a gallant defence followed, but the candle was soon knocked

05:01.950 --> 05:07.250
down or blown out, and then there was a glad clamour of laughter and a new chase. But all

05:07.250 --> 05:12.050
things have an end. By and by the procession went filing down the steep descent of the

05:12.050 --> 05:17.670
main avenue, the flickering rank of lights dimly revealing the lofty walls of rock almost

05:17.670 --> 05:23.030
to their point of junction sixty feet overhead. This main avenue was not more than eight or

05:23.030 --> 05:28.850
ten feet wide. Every few steps other lofty and still narrower crevices branched from

05:28.850 --> 05:34.790
it on either hand, for MacDougall's cave was but a vast labyrinth of crooked aisles that

05:34.790 --> 05:40.250
ran into each other and out again and led nowhere. It was said that one might wander

05:40.250 --> 05:45.430
days and nights together through its intricate tangle of rifts and chasms, and never find

05:45.430 --> 05:50.030
the end of the cave, and that he might go down and down and still down into the earth,

05:50.030 --> 05:56.630
and it was just the same—labyrinth, underneath labyrinth, and no end to any of them. No man

05:56.630 --> 06:02.390
knew the cave. That was an impossible thing. Most of the young men knew a portion of it,

06:02.430 --> 06:07.870
and it was not customary to venture much beyond this known portion. Tom Sawyer knew as much

06:07.870 --> 06:13.010
of the cave as any one. The procession moved along the main avenue some three quarters

06:13.010 --> 06:18.670
of a mile, then groups and couples began to slip aside into branch avenues, fly along

06:18.670 --> 06:22.810
the dismal corridors, and take each other by surprise at points where the corridors

06:22.810 --> 06:27.650
joined again. Parties were able to elude each other for the space of half an hour without

06:27.650 --> 06:33.950
going beyond the known ground. By and by one group after another came straggling back to

06:33.950 --> 06:39.230
the mouth of the cave, panting, hilarious, smeared from head to foot with tallow-drippings,

06:39.730 --> 06:44.870
daubed with clay, and entirely delighted with the success of the day. Then they were astonished

06:44.870 --> 06:50.650
that they had been taking no note of time, and that night was about at hand. The clanging

06:50.650 --> 06:55.810
bell had been calling for half an hour. However, this sort of close to the day's adventures

06:55.810 --> 07:01.530
was romantic and therefore satisfactory. When the ferry-boat with her wild freight pushed

07:01.530 --> 07:06.670
into the stream, nobody cared sixpence for the wasted time but the captain of the craft.

07:07.730 --> 07:12.590
Huck was already upon his watch when the ferry-boat's lights went glinting past the wharf. He heard

07:12.590 --> 07:17.750
no noise on board, for the young people were as subdued and still as people usually are

07:17.750 --> 07:23.050
who were nearly tired to death. He wondered what boat it was, and why she did not stop

07:23.050 --> 07:27.430
at the wharf, and then he dropped her out of his mind and put his attention upon his

07:27.430 --> 07:33.030
business. The night was growing cloudy and dark. Ten o'clock came, and the noise of the

07:33.030 --> 07:38.970
vehicle ceased. Scattered lights began to wink out. All straggling foot-passengers disappeared.

07:39.280 --> 07:44.570
The village betook itself to its slumbers and left the small watcher alone with the

07:44.570 --> 07:49.750
silence and the ghosts. Eleven o'clock came, and the tavern lights were put out. Darkness

07:49.750 --> 07:56.630
everywhere now. Huck waited what seemed a weary long time, but nothing happened. His

07:56.630 --> 08:03.610
faith was weakening. Was there any use? Was there really any use? Why not give it up and

08:03.610 --> 08:04.190
turn in?

08:04.730 --> 08:10.530
A noise fell upon his ear. He was all attention in an instant. The alley-door closed softly.

08:10.970 --> 08:16.090
He sprang to the corner of the brick-store. The next moment two men brushed by him, and

08:16.090 --> 08:20.990
one seemed to have something under his arm. It must be that box. So they were going to

08:20.990 --> 08:26.350
remove the treasurer. Why call Tom now? It would be absurd. The men would get away with

08:26.350 --> 08:31.050
the box and never be found again. No, he would stick to their wake and follow them. He would

08:31.050 --> 08:36.510
trust to the darkness for security from discovery. So communing with himself, Huck stepped out

08:36.510 --> 08:41.570
and glided along behind the men, cat-like, with bare feet, allowing them to keep just

08:41.570 --> 08:46.490
far enough ahead not to be invisible. They moved up the river-street three blocks, then

08:46.490 --> 08:51.170
turned to the left up a cross-street. They went straight ahead, then, until they came

08:51.170 --> 08:56.610
to the path that led up Cardiff Hill. This they took. They passed by the old Welshman's

08:56.610 --> 09:02.850
house, half-way up the hill, without hesitating, and still climbed upward. Good thought, Huck!

09:03.070 --> 09:07.990
They will bury it in the old quarry. But they never stopped at the quarry. They passed on

09:07.990 --> 09:13.750
up the summit. They plunged into the narrow path between the tall Sumac bushes and were

09:13.750 --> 09:15.090
at once hidden in the gloom.

09:15.610 --> 09:20.270
Huck closed up and shortened his distance now, for they would never be able to see him.

09:20.470 --> 09:25.630
He trotted along a while, then slackened his pace, fearing he was gaining too fast, moved

09:25.630 --> 09:31.970
on apiece, then stopped altogether, listened. No sound. None, save that he seemed to hear

09:31.970 --> 09:36.570
the beating of his own heart. The hooting of an owl came from over the hill. Ominous

09:36.570 --> 09:43.290
sound! But no footsteps. Heavens! Was everything lost? He was about to spring with winged feet

09:43.290 --> 09:45.870
when a man cleared his throat not four feet from him.

09:46.530 --> 09:51.430
Huck's heart shot into his throat, but he swallowed it again, and then he stood there,

09:51.430 --> 09:57.130
shaking as if a dozen agues had taken charge of him at once, and so weak that he thought

09:57.130 --> 10:03.150
he must surely fall to the ground. He knew where he was. He knew he was within five steps

10:03.150 --> 10:08.830
of the stile leading into Widow Douglas's grounds. Very well, he thought, let them bury

10:08.830 --> 10:10.970
it there. It won't be hard to find.

10:11.650 --> 10:15.810
Now there was a voice, a very low voice, Injun Joe's.

10:16.370 --> 10:21.290
Damn her! Maybe she's got company. There's lights, late as it is.

10:21.870 --> 10:27.130
I can't see any. This was that stranger's voice, the stranger of the haunted house.

10:27.550 --> 10:33.850
A deadly chill went to Huck's heart. This, then, was the revenge job. His thought was

10:33.850 --> 10:38.570
to fly. Then he remembered that the Widow Douglas had been kind to him more than once,

10:38.770 --> 10:43.950
and maybe these men were going to murder her. He wished he dared venture to warn her, but

10:43.950 --> 10:48.910
he knew he didn't dare. They might come and catch him. He thought all this and more in

10:48.910 --> 10:52.950
the moment that the lapse between the stranger's remark and Injun Joe's next, which was,

10:53.170 --> 10:58.830
"'Because the bush is in your way. Now this way. Now you see, don't you?'

10:58.830 --> 11:03.330
"'Yes. Well, there is company there, I reckon. Better give it up.'

11:03.330 --> 11:08.750
"'Give it up? And I just leaving this country forever? Give it up, and maybe never have

11:08.750 --> 11:13.350
another chance? I tell you again, as I've told you before, I don't care for her swag.

11:13.350 --> 11:19.210
You may have it. But her husband was rough on me. Many times he was rough on me. And

11:19.210 --> 11:23.690
mainly he was the justice of the peace that jugged me for a vagrant. And that ain't all.

11:23.930 --> 11:29.030
It ain't a millionth part of it. He had me horse-whipped. Horse-whipped in front of the

11:29.030 --> 11:34.270
jail, like a nigger, with all the town looking on. Horse-whipped, do you understand? He took

11:34.270 --> 11:37.550
advantage of me and died, but I'll take it out of her.'

11:38.210 --> 11:44.250
"'Oh, don't kill her. Don't do that. Kill? Who said anything about killing? I would kill

11:44.250 --> 11:48.450
him if he were here, but not her. When you want to get revenge on a woman, you don't

11:48.450 --> 11:54.290
kill her. Bosh, you go for her looks. You slit her nostrils. You knot your ears, like

11:54.290 --> 11:56.690
a sow. By God, that's—'

11:57.270 --> 12:01.730
"'Keep your opinion to yourself. It will be safest for you. I'll tie her to the bed.

12:02.130 --> 12:07.530
If she bleeds to death, is that my fault? I'll not cry if she does. My friend, you'll

12:07.530 --> 12:11.950
get help in this thing, for my sake. That's why you're here. I mightn't be able to loan.

12:12.410 --> 12:16.790
If you flinch, I'll kill you. Do you understand that? And if I have to kill you, I'll kill

12:16.790 --> 12:22.290
her. And then I reckon nobody'll ever know much about who done this business. Well, if

12:22.290 --> 12:28.230
it's got to be done, let's get at it. The quicker the better. I'm all in a shiver. Do

12:28.230 --> 12:34.050
it now? And company there? Look here, I'll get suspicious of you. First thing you know—no,

12:34.050 --> 12:37.110
we'll wait till the lights are out. There's no hurry."

12:37.110 --> 12:41.970
Huck felt that a silence was going to ensue—a thing still more awful than any amount of

12:41.970 --> 12:47.330
murderous talk. So he held his breath and stepped gingerly back, planted his foot carefully

12:47.330 --> 12:53.470
and firmly, after balancing, one-legged, in a precarious way, and almost toppling over,

12:53.690 --> 12:59.070
first on one side and then on the other. He took another step back, with the same elaboration

12:59.070 --> 13:07.590
and the same risks, then another and another, and—a twig snapped under his foot. His breath

13:07.590 --> 13:13.910
stopped when he listened. There was no sound. The stillness was perfect. His gratitude was

13:13.910 --> 13:18.850
measureless. Now he turned in his tracks, between the walls of sumac bushes, turned

13:18.850 --> 13:23.230
himself as carefully as if he were a ship, and then stepped quickly but cautiously along.

13:23.590 --> 13:28.590
When he emerged at the quarry he felt secure, and so he picked up his nimble heels and flew,

13:28.590 --> 13:35.250
down, down he sped till he reached the Welshman's. He banged at the door, and presently the

13:35.250 --> 13:39.150
heads of the old man and his two stalwart sons were thrust from the windows.

13:39.510 --> 13:42.130
"'What's the row there? Who's banging? What do you want?'

13:42.130 --> 13:44.470
"'Let me in, quick! I'll tell everything.'

13:44.470 --> 13:46.010
"'Why, who are you?'

13:46.010 --> 13:48.710
"'Huckleberry Finn! Quick, let me in!'

13:48.710 --> 13:53.510
"'Huckleberry Finn, indeed. It ain't a name to open many doors, I judge. But let him in,

13:53.710 --> 13:55.230
lads, and let's see what's the trouble.'

13:55.230 --> 13:59.630
"'Please don't ever tell I told you,' were Huck's first words when he got in.

13:59.870 --> 14:04.770
"'Please don't. I'd be killed, sure. But the widow's been good friends to me sometimes,

14:04.770 --> 14:09.150
and I want to tell. I will tell, if you'll promise you won't ever say it was me.'

14:09.150 --> 14:14.150
"'By George, he has got something to tell, or he wouldn't act so,' exclaimed the old

14:14.150 --> 14:14.470
man.

14:14.770 --> 14:17.850
"'Out with it, and nobody here'll ever tell, lad.'

14:17.850 --> 14:22.210
Three minutes later the old man and his sons, well armed, were up the hill and just entering

14:22.210 --> 14:27.210
the Sumac path on tiptoe, their weapons in their hands. Huck accompanied them no farther.

14:27.570 --> 14:32.270
He hid behind a great boulder and fell to listening. There was a lagging, anxious silence,

14:32.490 --> 14:37.730
and then all of a sudden there was an explosion of firearms and a cry. Huck waited for no

14:37.730 --> 14:42.350
particulars. He sprang away and sped down the hill as fast as his legs could carry him.'

14:42.350 --> 14:45.470
End of chapter 29

